Teotihuacan: Ceramics, Chronology and Cultural Trends. EVELYN CHILDS RATTRAY. Series Arque­ol6gica de Mexico, Instituto Nacional de Antropologfa e Historia/University of Pittsburgh, 2001. 414 pp., fig­ures, tables, maps, references. $65.00 (paper). 
Reviewed by Dean E. Arnold, Wheaton College. 
This monumental volume represents a massive effort of synthesis, organization, and presentation of the 
ceramic chronology of Teotihuacan. With its 704 pages, it brings together an immense amount of material for both English and Spanish readers. The Spanish text (on even numbered pages) and English text (on odd num­bered pages) are placed together for ease of use by speakers of either language, but common texts do not always match up across the page from each other. Once one realizes that the unnumbered blank pages are not a printing error (the Spanish text is significantly longer), one appreciates the synergy of having the bilingual text together. 
The volume is organized into four chapters and a final summary that ties the ceramics and the cultural trends together. The 414 pages of text are supple­mented with 17 pages of references, 181 pages of maps, excavation profiles, vessel photos and sherd drawings, and 75 pages of tables showing the fre­quencies of ceramic wares by phase and by excava­tion unit. For those interested in color renderings of some of the black and white photos, readers are directed to the Latin American Archaeology Database at: <http://www.pitt.edu/-laad>. 
In the Introduction, Evelyn Rattray lays out the three objectives of the book: 1) to establish the chronology of Teotihuacan ceramics from the begin­ning of the Christian era to A.D. 650, 2) to present accurate and comprehensive descriptions of the ceramic complexes of each phase, and 3) to integrate these data with those from previous and current work in the area (p. 29). The pottery for her study consisted of approximately 200,000 sherds from 26 excava­tions. One segment consisted of 120,800 sherds from "stratigraphic pits" while other material consisted of sherds from surface survey, from published and unpublished sources, and complete vessels from bur­ial offerings in apartment compounds that were exca­vated by INAH archaeologists. Rather than new terminology, Rattray "used simple descriptive terms for wares and types now in common usage among archaeologists in central Mexico" (p. 33). "My task," she says, "has been to process the enormous body of ceramic material from the excavations, search for evi­dence of empirical variation and revise and refine the 'old' chronology, correcting the existing categories as data permitted" (p. 33). Judged by her own standard of the comprehensiveness of her task, she has been enormously successful, but I will leave the evaluation of her revisions and corrections of the chronology to Teotihuacan specialists. 
Besides the empirical sample used for the chronol­ogy, Rattray describes the previous work on the sub­ject, and details the methodology that she used. She gave classificatory (and therefore implicitly theoreti­cal) priority to "ware" in her classification with the 
