The way in which Rattray relates her classification to actual human behavior, however, is another matter: "A ware usually has a center of manufacture housed in one or several households or workshops and is the production of a group of people who share a common cultural tradition" (p. 41). Citing her ethnographic work with Paula Krotser as an example, she says: "The potters collect their clay from a specific source and prepare it according to a set of learned proce­dures .... In classifying wares, the archaeologist is attempting to recognize the products of workshops" 
(p. 41). Unfortunately, this relationship of "ware" to production unit/s is too fuzzy, and is based too much on synchronic ethnography. It implies that raw mater­ial sources are singular and raw materials and paste preparation techniques are unchangeable because they are "cultural" and "traditional." This assumption does not appear to account for the 
fact that ceramic resources and potter's choices in the production of the ceramic fabric change over time. As ethnographic studies of potter's raw materials have shown, raw materials may be highly variable in composition and may come from multiple and geographically diverse sources and they, and the potters' preparation tech­niques, may change over time. Further, production units may produce more than one "ware." When pot­ters use common, and relatively uniform raw materi­als and preparation techniques, individual production units cannot be differentiated at all within a "ware" category (as defined here), but rather "wares" might better correspond to different communities even lem cannot be solved by classifying potsherds with more precision and reliability, but rather by examin­ing the social and cultural theory of ceramic produc­tion hidden in assumptions that lurk unseen behind every ceramic typology. As important as this monu­mental book is, one must, nevertheless, think about going beyond traditional classifications if one is going to say more about the unwritten past. 

The second chapter details the excavation loca­tions within the city that were used in the analysis and describes the stratigraphy of each along with those locations with burials. 
Chapter 3 presents the Teotihuacan ceramics of local manufacture based upon a sample of sherds ana­lyzed by petrography and neutron activation. This chapter is "a study of the evolution of ceramic style, of decoration and of form of Teotihuacan ceramics" 
(p. 87), and its purpose is to "provide a precise chronological record of the changes in clay artifacts" that can be used to date features within the city and sites outside of it. Here again, she organizes her pre­sentation by ceramic complexes and wares based upon criteria of paste composition and style and links the ceramics with local geology and clays as well as local ceramics made in the area today. 
Most interesting in this chapter is the brief discus­sion of molds for the production of cooking pottery and figurines. The description of making a cooking pot using a mold and coils (p. 237) appears to be iden­tical to that used in three communities of Maya Pokomam speakers (Chinautla, Sacojito, and Durazno) in central Guatemala just a few kilometers north of the ancient Teotihuacan-influenced site of Kaminaljuyu. My own ethnographic work has shown that forming technologies are the most conservative of all ceramic attributes, and recent ethnographic work 
