In fairness to Rattray, this disconnect between archaeological classification and ethnographic reali­ties of potters' behavior is all too common in the use of ceramic typology. Certainly, monumental works like Rattray's are extremely important for those who are trying to make sense out of hundreds of thousands of potsherds from a site like Teotihuacan in order to use them for relative dating. Nevertheless, a middle­range theory based upon cross-cultural and diachronic ethnoarchaeological work is needed to tie ceramic classification (the "type/variety" technique) to the realities of differing production scales such as house­hold, workshop, community, and region. This prob-forming techniques still remain long after linguistic and ethnic affiliations of a population have disap­peared. Does the similarity of forming technique between central Mexico and central Guatemala sug­gest the transport of potters in one direction or the other? 
Chapter 4 presents the foreign ceramics, most notably the thin orange ware that was "Teotihuacan's most important and prestigious 'trade ceramic"' (p. 305) and was imported from 250 km away at Tepexi de 
Rodriguez in the Southern part of the State of Puebla. After a brief history of its archaeological importance, Rattray describes the ware with a sum­mary of the petrographic and neutron activation analyses of it. She then details the thin orange types according to phases and elaborates the modes of sur­face finish, form, and paste. 


